Magazine Discover our stories About Creating Chemistry Awarded again and again
Subscription Creating Chemistry Magazine Download Manager Contact What do we
actually know? Experts give us some answers from their own perspective.
Looking for products? Go to Product Finder Global Media From different
perspectives What do we know? Home Media Magazine What do we know? December
29, 2022 Global Media Wenn Abfall wegfällt Informing ourselves sufficiently to
make the right decisions is often difficult, particularly when it comes to
complex issues. Who can we believe and trust? Creating Chemistry asked several
experts about how we gather knowledge when much is at stake. Covid-19 has
revealed how unprepared we were for a global pandemic. It also showed how
unprepared most of us are to deal with the scientific discovery of truth
happening live before our eyes. Scientists have disagreed over everything from
where the virus comes from to how dangerous it is and how to tackle it –
leaving many bewildered and distrustful. It has shown that a healthy society
needs citizens who know how to obtain balanced information and form their own
judgements. Covid-19 has revealed how unprepared we were for a global
pandemic. It also showed how unprepared most of us are to deal with the
scientific discovery of truth happening live before our eyes. Scientists have
disagreed over everything from where the virus comes from to how dangerous it
is and how to tackle it – leaving many bewildered and distrustful. It has
shown that a healthy society needs citizens who know how to obtain balanced
information and form their own judgements. A science journalist, a
disinformation expert and a philosopher weighed in for Creating Chemistry.
They noted that the general public does not realize that science is sometimes
genuinely uncertain and disputed; that conspiracy theories are often a cry of
protest from a minority who feel unheard and powerless; and that, for nearly
everyone, trust is crucial for acquiring knowledge. A BASF scientist closes
with reflections on the ongoing European battle over acceptance, or not, of
genetically engineered crops. Transparency and communication are still the
keys to good public decision-making, he says, knowing that this is far easier
to say than to do. Our experts Loading ... Science is not always about
certainty The science journalist Science is not always about certainty
“Listening to what people really want to know is the best way to communicate
science.” To the interview with Volker Stollorz Conspiracy theories cannot
just be dismissed The disinformation expert Conspiracy theories cannot just be
dismissed “Dispute, challenge and skepticism are part of democracy. We need
critics, and we need to accept that some criticisms will be wrong.” To the
interview with Thaiane Oliveira The truth is out there waiting for us to find
it The philosopher The truth is out there waiting for us to find it “What is
important is that we base our actions on the amount of information that we
have available at the time.” To the interview with Mona Simion Constructive
dialogue must acknowledge different beliefs The biologist Constructive
dialogue must acknowledge different beliefs “Instead of an us-and-them
approach, we ask how we can jointly define value for society.” To the
statement of Matthias Pohl Tags: #Society Creating Chemistry magazine 2022
